        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down</placeName>
                    <date>November 4th,</date>
                    <salute>My dear Falconer</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>What a good kind friend you are. I know well that this medal must have cost you a deal of trouble.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It is a very great honour to me, but I declare the knowledge that you and a few other friends<ref target="#foot.f3"/> have so much interested themselves on the subject is the real cream of the enjoyment to me; indeed it is to me worth far more than many medals. So accept my true and cordial thanks. I hope that I may yet have strength to do a little more work in natural science; shaky and old though I be. I have chuckled and triumphed over your postscript about poor M. Brullé and his young pupils.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> About a week ago I had a nearly similar account from Germany and at the same time I heard of some splendid converts in such men as Leuckart, Gegenbaur &amp;c.<ref target="#foot.f5"/> You may say what you like about yourself, but I look at a man who treats Natural History in the spirit with which you do, exactly as good for what <hi rend="underline">I believe</hi> to be the truth, as a convert.<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
<p>Farewell my good friend with sincere thanks | Your true friend | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4652.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hugh Falconer, 3 November 186[4]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD refers to the Copley Medal. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4652.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hugh Falconer, 3 November 186[4]</ref> and n. 2. See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4644.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hugh Falconer to William Sharpey, 25 October 1864</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4652.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hugh Falconer, 3 November 186[4]</ref> and n. 3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_692.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Gaspard Auguste Brullé</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4652.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hugh Falconer, 3 November 186[4]</ref> and n. 7.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4646.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Ernst Haeckel, 26 October 1864</ref> and n. 5. Haeckel mentioned <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2908.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Rudolf Leuckart</ref> and Carl Gegenbaur as being among the converts to CD’s theory.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4652.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hugh Falconer, 3 November 186[4]</ref> and n. 4.</note>
        </div>        
            
